tasks.prompt:
On server startup Paperclip reaps orphaned runs. After a normal restart, runs that were still 'running' are being permanently FAILED as 'process_lost' instead of being resumed — even though nothing was actually wrong with them.

Relevant code:

  // index.ts startup
  reapOrphanedRuns()                     // called with no argument

  function reapOrphanedRuns(staleThresholdMs = 0) {
    const cutoff = Date.now() - staleThresholdMs
    for (const run of runningRuns()) {
      if (run.lastHeartbeatAt <= cutoff) {
        failRun(run, 'process_lost')       // shouldRetry=false on a bare restart -> permanent
      }
    }
  }

In under 110 words: (1) state the exact bug, (2) why every still-running run gets failed on a clean restart, and (3) the fix. Be precise about the default value and the comparison.

This TypeScript loads routine cards and runs slowly under load.

  async function loadRoutineCards(routineIds: string[]) {
    const cards = [];
    for (const id of routineIds) {
      const routine = await db.query.routines.findFirst({ where: eq(routines.id, id) });
      const runs = await db.query.runs.findMany({ where: eq(runs.routineId, id), limit: 5 });
      cards.push({ routine, runs });
    }
    return cards;
  }

In under 130 words: (1) name the performance problem precisely, (2) explain why it scales badly, and (3) give the corrected approach (you may sketch code) that fetches the data in a bounded number of queries instead of per-routine. Be specific.

This TypeScript endpoint lets an OpCo CEO look up one of their own routines by name from the admin console. `db.execute` runs the raw string against Postgres.

  app.get('/admin/routine', async (req, res) => {
    const name = req.query.name;            // user-supplied
    const rows = await db.execute(
      `SELECT id, schedule, last_run FROM routines WHERE name = '${name}'`
    );
    res.json(rows);
  });

In under 120 words: (1) name the vulnerability precisely and give one concrete input string that exploits it, (2) state the worst-case impact given this runs against the shared multi-OpCo database, and (3) give the corrected query using the right mechanism. Be specific about WHY the fix closes it.

An engineer opens this migration against the live Paperclip Postgres (the `heartbeat_runs` table has ~40M rows and is written on every agent heartbeat, continuously, in production):

  -- migration 0042
  ALTER TABLE heartbeat_runs ADD COLUMN cost_cents integer NOT NULL DEFAULT 0;
  UPDATE heartbeat_runs SET cost_cents = (usage_json->>'costUsd')::numeric * 100;
  CREATE INDEX idx_hr_cost ON heartbeat_runs (cost_cents);

They plan to run it inline during business hours. Review it for production safety.

In under 140 words: (1) identify each statement that will lock the table or block writes and why that takes the heartbeat path down, (2) call out the single-transaction backfill problem on 40M rows, and (3) give a safe rewrite (statement ordering, locking, backfill strategy, index build). Be concrete about Postgres locking behavior.

This TypeScript handles a Stripe webhook for a successful OpCo product sale. Stripe delivers each event AT LEAST ONCE and retries on any non-2xx response or timeout, so the same `checkout.session.completed` event can arrive multiple times.

  app.post('/webhook/stripe', async (req, res) => {
    const event = req.body;
    if (event.type === 'checkout.session.completed') {
      const sale = event.data.object;
      await db.insert(orders).values({ sessionId: sale.id, amount: sale.amount_total });
      await grantProductAccess(sale.customer);     // also emails a license key
      await incrementRevenueCounter(sale.amount_total);
    }
    res.sendStatus(200);
  });

In under 130 words: (1) name the bug class precisely, (2) describe the concrete bad outcome when Stripe redelivers the same event, and (3) give the fix that makes the handler safe under redelivery. Be specific about what makes an operation idempotent here.

Paperclip's daily usage report should aggregate all heartbeat_runs for ONE calendar day in the OpCo's local timezone (Europe/Dublin, currently UTC+1 in summer). `created_at` is stored in Postgres as `timestamptz` (UTC). This code builds the window:

  // report for the day given by `dayStr` e.g. '2026-06-20'
  const start = new Date(dayStr + 'T00:00:00Z');        // 2026-06-20 00:00 UTC
  const end   = new Date(dayStr + 'T23:59:59Z');        // 2026-06-20 23:59 UTC
  const rows = await db.select().from(heartbeatRuns)
    .where(and(gte(heartbeatRuns.createdAt, start), lte(heartbeatRuns.createdAt, end)));

CEOs report the totals are slightly off and a run at 00:30 local time lands in the wrong day's report.

In under 130 words: (1) name BOTH defects precisely (the timezone defect AND the boundary defect), (2) explain concretely which runs get mis-bucketed and into which day, and (3) give the corrected window. Be specific about the offset and the boundary comparison.
